FILE: 02-players/06-fermions/6.2.md L549
CONTENT: The proof employs formal induction on the ribbon count $n$, verifying that configurations with $n < 3$ ribbons fail either topological stability (absence of non-trivial invariants or susceptibility to local decay under $\mathcal{R}$ [(§4.5.1)](/monograph/rules/dynamics/4.5/#4.5.1)) or algebraic sufficiency (inability to generate non-abelian $\mathfrak{su}(3)$ for QCD). Configurations with $n > 3$ ribbons surpass minimality per the Minimal Generation Theorem, introducing superfluous complexity (elevated $C[\beta]$) absent qualitative innovations for the first generation. This induction harmonizes with Axiom 2 in [(§2.3.1)](/monograph/rules/axioms/2.3/#2.3.1) and the general cycle decomposition in [(§2.4.1)](/monograph/rules/axioms/2.4/#2.4.1), where 3-cycles serve as minimal quanta ensuring non-trivial topology for excitations, and non-prime structures reduce under $\mathcal{R}$ to preserve primeness.
PART/CHAP: players/fermions
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FILE: 02-players/06-fermions/6.2.md L551
CONTENT: **Step 1: Base Case ($n=0$).** Unbraided structures correspond to $n=0$. [(§6.2.3)](/monograph/players/fermions/6.2/#6.2.3) establishes topological triviality and instability, with $\sigma = -1$ catalyzing decay.
PART/CHAP: players/fermions
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FILE: 02-players/06-fermions/6.2.md L553
CONTENT: **Step 2: Base Case ($n=1$).** Single-ribbon structures correspond to $n=1$. [(§6.2.4)](/monograph/players/fermions/6.2/#6.2.4) demonstrates reducibility via Type II moves, lacking non-trivial topology for protection.
PART/CHAP: players/fermions
