FILE: 02-players/06-fermions/6.3.md L46
CONTENT: While crossings add mass linearly, twisting a ribbon adds mass quadratically. This distinction arises from the specific geometry of the discrete lattice. Twisting a ribbon once creates a local strain in the graph connections. A subsequent twist cannot simply be superimposed; the causal path must wind *around* the existing obstruction to avoid violating the **Principle of Unique Causality** [(§2.3.3)](/monograph/rules/axioms/2.3/#2.3.3), which forbids cloning edges or reusing paths.
