FILE: 02-players/07-topology/7.2.md L159
CONTENT: Consider a macroscopic filament. A local observer viewing a small segment perceives the local twist but cannot count the *total* number of twists in the entire filament without traversing its length. Since the rewrite rule cannot traverse the particle instantaneously due to the causal horizon [(§6.4.3)](/monograph/players/fermions/6.4/#6.4.3), it remains blind to the total charge. This blindness manifests as a symmetry. The local laws of physics must remain invariant under shifts in the global writhe count. Whether the total writhe is $W$ or $W+1$, the local dynamics appear identical. This invariance necessitates the existence of a compensating field to maintain consistency across the graph, precisely the role of the photon field in quantum electrodynamics. Gauge symmetry follows not as a postulate but as a consequence of the limited horizon of local causal operations.
