FILE: 02-players/10-computation/10.5.md L117
CONTENT: The **color phase lemma** [(§10.5.3)](/monograph/players/computation/10.5/#10.5.3) proves that the excited state interacts. Because it has a "lumpy" (asymmetric) charge distribution, the gauge field gets tangled up in its topology. As the system evolves, this entanglement imprints a specific phase shift, a minus sign, onto the wavefunction. This is the Aharonov-Bohm effect for color charge. By tuning the interaction, the calibration ensures this phase is exactly 180 degrees (flipping the sign), creating the "Z" part of the Z-gate. This links the abstract concept of a phase gate to the concrete physics of gauge field interactions.
