FILE: 02-players/10-computation/10.9.md L343
CONTENT: Yet the simulation spotlights QBD's stakes: if the causal graph [(§1.3)](/monograph/rules/ontology/1.3/#1.3) computes universally [(§10.9.1)](/monograph/players/computation/10.9/#10.9.1), braid particles [(§6.2)](/monograph/players/fermions/6.2/#6.2) as qubits and rewrites as gates [(§10.4-10.8)](/monograph/players/computation/10.4/#10.4) imply scalable hardware from geometric vacuum [(§5.4)](/monograph/rules/equilibrium/5.4/#5.4), potentially compressing that timeline. The $d=3$ code's resilience here (off-peaks $<0.3\%$, $P=1.00$ decoding) previews self-correcting systems via syndrome catalysis [(§10.2.9)](/monograph/players/computation/10.2/#10.2.9), where errors evaporate thermodynamically [(§4.6.3)](/monograph/rules/dynamics/4.6/#4.6.3), a boon for non-crypto apps like protein folding or fusion optimization. This potential for scalable, fault-tolerant computation directly addresses the "quantum supremacy" threshold discussed by **[(Acharya et al., 2024)](/monograph/appendices/a-references#A.3)**, suggesting that topological substrates may offer a more direct path to utility than noisy intermediate-scale quantum (NISQ) devices.
